#Using ProtonMail

2015-06-21

<!--- tags: encryption -->

[ProtonMail](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ProtonMail) has a nice feature to send protected messages to other people that do not use [ProtonMail](https://protonmail.ch/). Unlike with PGP, it is not for communicating party to take the encryption initiative, they only react. While the process is very simple for the non-ProtonMail recipients, it still is up to the ProtonMail user to explain how this works to others.

ProtonMail user has to agree upfront with her communicating party on some shared secret password. Once you send an email from within ProtonMail protected with that password, the communicating party will receive an email message that looks as follows:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)


Clicking on the 'View Secure Message' link, opens a *protomail.ch* web page in system web browser that asks the secure message recipient for the agreed shared password:


![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)


Once the recipient enters the agreed password, she can read the secure message and the choose 'Reply Securely' if she wants to answer it.


![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)


Once the reply text is written, 'Send Securely' button will send the secure email to the ProtonMail user.


![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)


The ProtoMail user can then respond again securely using same or another agreed shared password and this whole process can be repeated as many times as needed.

ProtonMail only protects the message body text, not the attachments, nor the subject, nor any other metadata. The maximum lifetime of such protected messages is four weeks.
